<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 40 companion (taming an inherited disaster — the ordered remediation playbook, and the
    type-aware automation engine that scales the craft). The chapter is a synthesis, so the module makes
    the two load-bearing claims runnable rather than asserted: (a) the ORDERED PLAYBOOK as data the test
    walks (assess/baseline -> gate new -> safety net -> hotspot paydown -> strangle -> sustain), with the
    prioritization rule (remediate by churn x pain; debt in frozen code accrues no interest) as a
    runnable ranker the tests exercise; and (b) the AUTOMATION ENGINE — an OpenRewrite recipe
    (config/rewrite/rewrite.yml) plus the before/after Java pair the recipe would transform, both
    compiling green now. The printed config and the running config are one artifact.

    The OpenRewrite recipe RUN is network-gated (the rewrite-maven-plugin and the recipe modules resolve
    from the network, not the local cache), so it lives in an opt-in `rewrite` profile and is REPRO
    PENDING-RUNTIME — the chapter's "automation proposes, tests dispose" point, honestly scoped. The
    default build and the `quality` build need none of that: the prioritization logic, the playbook
    model, and the before/after Java compile and test green offline.

    The module is held to its own gates (the `quality` profile) and stays green BECAUSE the legacy
    before-form is isolated in a `legacy` package the gate baselines, not because the code is empty of
    debt — the chapter's whole point made executable. Runtime dependencies are JDK-only; the one extra
    compile-path GAV is the SpotBugs annotations artifact, exactly as the Chapter 39 module does.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>remediation-playbook-automated-change</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 40 — Taming the Inherited Disaster (remediation-playbook-automated-change)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      SpotBugs annotations (SOURCE-PIN.md: SpotBugs 4.10.2 line; this module builds against the locally
      cached 4.9.3 engine the companion code is pinned to, so the annotations track that engine). Carries
      @SuppressFBWarnings(value, justification) from edu.umd.cs.findbugs.annotations for the one reviewed
      false positive at its site. CLASS-retained (SpotBugs reads bytecode), so `provided` keeps it on the
      compile path only and the module's runtime stays JDK-only like the rest of the companion code.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
      <artifactId>spotbugs-annotations</artifactId>
      <version>4.9.3</version>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <profiles>
    <!--
      The static-analysis gates, opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays fast. Same shape as the
      Chapter 39 module: Checkstyle (the source view) and SpotBugs (the bytecode view), each reading config
      under this module's own config/ dir (self-contained). The maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled
      engine (Checkstyle 9.3); the pinned house engine is pulled in as a plugin-level dependency (the
      "two-pin" lesson — the build plugin and the analyzer engine are versioned separately).
    -->
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Low</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>

    <!--
      The automation engine, opt-in via `-Prewrite`. This wires the OpenRewrite Maven plugin at the pinned
      version (SOURCE-PIN.md §6: OpenRewrite 8.81.0; rewrite-maven-plugin 6.38.0) and points it at the
      declarative recipe under config/rewrite/rewrite.yml. It is DELIBERATELY NOT part of the default or
      `quality` build: the plugin and the recipe modules resolve from the network, so a clean offline build
      cannot run it. This is the chapter's honesty made structural — the recipe RUN is REPRO PENDING-RUNTIME,
      while the recipe config, the before/after pair, and the prioritization logic are all verified offline.

        Apply the recipe (writes the diff to review as a PR):  mvn -Prewrite rewrite:run
        Preview without writing (dry run):                     mvn -Prewrite rewrite:dryRun

      The recipe module GAV (rewrite-migrate-java) and the recipe IDs named in rewrite.yml are
      verify-at-pin against docs.openrewrite.org at the pinned line — see the chapter's _EXAMPLE.md and the
      09-flags/ note. Automation proposes; the tests and the review still dispose.
    -->
    <profile>
      <id>rewrite</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.openrewrite.maven</groupId>
            <artifactId>rewrite-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>6.38.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>${project.basedir}/config/rewrite/rewrite.yml</configLocation>
              <activeRecipes>
                <recipe>org.acme.remediation.ModernizeForJava21</recipe>
              </activeRecipes>
            </configuration>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>org.openrewrite.recipe</groupId>
                <artifactId>rewrite-migrate-java</artifactId>
                <version>3.16.0</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
